t an adaptive learning control approach inspired by human motor learning to improve the system's adaptability to different sound environments. This approach will use a composite error learning technique to adjust the model parameters dynamically.\n\n3. **Training and Evaluation:**\n   - **Training:** Train the GRU model on a diverse dataset of sound signals from different machines. Use a combination of supervised and unsupervised learning techniques to handle the scarcity of labeled data.\n   - **Evaluation Metrics:** Use precision, recall, and F1-score to evaluate the performance of the anomaly detection system. Additionally, consider using the area under the receiver operating characteristic curve (AUC-ROC) to assess the model's ability to distinguish between normal and anomalous sounds.\n\n### Dataset Identification\n\n- **Dataset:** Use the **DCASE 2020 Challenge Dataset** for evaluating the proposed approach. This dataset contains a diverse collection of sound signals from different machines and environments, making it suitable for testing the system's ability to handle non-stationary sounds and different machine identities.\n- **Data Split:** Split the dataset into training, validation, and test sets. Use the training set to train the GRU model, the validation set to tune hyperparameters, and the test set to evaluate the final performance of the system.\n\n### Next Steps\n\n1. **Implementation:** Implement the proposed model architecture and training pipeline.\n2. **Evaluation:** Evaluate the model on the DCASE 2020 Challenge Dataset using the specified evaluation metrics.\n3. **Refinement:** Refine the model based on the evaluation results and gather feedback from peers or mentors.\n4. **Proposal Preparation:** Write a detailed research proposal based on the refined idea, including the methodology, expected outcomes, and significance of the research.\n\nBy following these steps, I aim to develop a robust and reliable anomaly detection system that leverages my expertise in GRUs and adaptive learning techniques. This system will be capable of handling non-stationary sounds and different machine identities, addressing the challenges faced by existing methods."}

